{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"20beea70-5e5e-46e2-93f6-1f843b940204","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues I found:\n\n---\n\n### 1. 🔴 Recursive wildcard glob (line 9 of `.csproj`)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` forces MSBuild to walk the **entire directory tree** during evaluation. This is the single most expensive evaluation pattern — cost scales with the number of files on disk, and it runs on every evaluation (IDE load, build, etc.). Narrow the glob to specific extensions or directories.\n\n### 2. 🟠 File I/O via property function (line 13)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nCalling `System.IO.File.ReadAllText` is **synchronous disk I/O during evaluation**. It blocks the evaluator and bypasses MSBuild's file-tracking. If the file is large or on a slow volume, this stalls every evaluation. Prefer a target-time `ReadLinesFromFile` task or pass the path and read it at build time instead.\n\n### 3. 🟡 Chained import depth (3 levels)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach `<Import>` adds an XML parse + evaluate pass. Three levels is moderate, but it's a pattern that compounds quickly. Flatten where possible or consolidate into a single `.props` file to reduce import depth.\n\n---\n\n**Priority order for fixing:** #1 (wildcard glob) ≫ #2 (file read) > #3 (import chain). The recursive glob dominates real-world evaluation time.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e7894e52-3093-4efa-9a34-dc8199cf4514","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a complete picture. Let me analyze the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project.","outputTokens":464},"id":"db3595be-2d66-4d8b-bcc3-4aaf8e9868d2","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:09:43.621Z","parentId":"ef2b20dd-603b-4966-9922-5e1772d2d76f"}
